<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-463-248  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 463 248.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  July 1989 v18 n9 p69(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Thou shalt not create worms: the drafter of Internet's ethicscode. (network security; profile of Vinton G. Cerf) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Strauss, Paul R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Networking expert Vinton G Cerf, one of the pioneers of Arpanetand a designer of the TCP/IP networking protocols, has drafted anethics code for network users aimed at preventing viruses and'worms' such as the Nov 88 attack on Internet.andP;  Cerf argues thatsuch incidents demonstrate 'irresponsible behavior' even when notmalicious and that laws should be passed which place the samevalue on intellectual as on physical property.andP;  His document drawsparallels between computer networks and public-utility systems,noting that frivolous or malicious behavior can harm or wastethem.andP;  Five 'commandments' delineate unethical activities,including deliberate disruption of any network, the gaining ofunauthorized access, and the wasting of network resources.andP;  Cerfnotes that defending a network against insiders is difficult andbelieves that users who willfully violate moral principles shouldbe shunned.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data SecurityComputer CrimeEthicsNetworks.andO;Person:    Cerf, Vinton G. (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>